# ai-agent-playbook — Cursor Rules
#
# These rules help Cursor understand the conventions of this repository
# so it can assist with creating and editing prompts, agents, skills, and workflows.

## Repository Purpose

This repo is a framework for managing AI prompts, agent instructions, reusable skills,
workflows, and experiments for LLM-powered systems. All artifacts are Markdown or YAML files.

## File Conventions

### Prompts (`prompts/`)
- Every `.md` file must begin with a YAML frontmatter block
- Required fields: `id`, `version`, `status`, `description`, `author`
- Naming: `<domain>-<intent>[-<variant>]-v<N>.md`
- Variables use `{{double_braces}}` syntax
- Production prompts require test cases in `eval/test-cases/`

### Agents (`agents/`)
- Each agent lives in its own folder: `agents/<domain>-<role>/`
- Required files: `agent.md`, `config.yaml`, `system-prompt.md`
- `agent.md` is the primary definition (human + AI readable)
- `config.yaml` contains only machine config (model, memory, guardrails)
- Skills are referenced as `ref: skills/<name>/SKILL.md`

### Skills (`skills/`)
- Each skill lives in its own folder: `skills/<domain>-<action>/`
- Required files: `SKILL.md` (definition), `config.yaml` (implementation)
- `SKILL.md` is always uppercase

### Workflows (`workflows/`)
- Each workflow lives in its own folder: `workflows/<name>/`
- Required files: `README.md`, `workflow.yaml`

## Naming Rules

- All file and folder names: lowercase kebab-case only
- Exception: `SKILL.md` is uppercase
- No spaces, underscores, or camelCase

## When Generating New Files

1. Always include required YAML frontmatter
2. Use `{{variable_name}}` for template variables — never hardcode values
3. Reference skills as `ref: skills/<name>/SKILL.md`
4. Add new agents/skills/workflows to their respective `_index.md`
5. Log changes in `changelog/CHANGELOG.md`

## Prompt Lifecycle

```
prompts/experimental/ → (review + test cases) → prompts/production/
```

Never edit an existing production prompt — create a new version file.
